   portfolio choice decisions. To explore these implications, we develop a
   continuous time investment and consumption model with capital gains tax,
   Epstein-Zin recursive utility, and regime switching. We find that
   various factors, such as tax rate, risk aversion, interest rate, stock
   return, and volatility, jointly affect optimal portfolio allocation,
   whereas intertemporal substitution does not. In a regime switching
   market, investors may trade or stop trading purely because of a change
   in regime, and there is a distinct cross-regime effect on optimal
